WEBVTT

00:02.440 --> 00:04.280
'Previously:' Jack, your wife
has had an accident.

00:04.280 --> 00:05.560
'Previously:' Jack, your wife
has had an accident.

00:05.560 --> 00:07.280
Nina's dead, Jack.  What?

00:07.280 --> 00:10.120
Now, I am performing this heart
transplant in 30 minutes.

00:10.120 --> 00:11.840
Mark, I don't want to die.

00:11.840 --> 00:13.200
I won't let you die.

00:13.200 --> 00:17.200
Donor, white female, age 28.
Name, Morrison, Nina L.

00:18.000 --> 00:21.240
If it's any comfort, your wife has
given that woman a second chance.

00:21.240 --> 00:23.680
The first 15 names
work Thanksgiving.

00:23.680 --> 00:25.200
'Tonight on St Elsewhere:'

00:25.200 --> 00:27.600
This  is  an emergency. Do you want
thousands of kids

00:27.600 --> 00:29.920
to watch big Snoopy die on national
television?

00:29.920 --> 00:32.840
Any turkey stuffed with fruit
is repulsive.

00:32.840 --> 00:35.960
I want a decent meal on Thanksgiving
I'll have to cook my own turkey.

00:35.960 --> 00:38.040
Halfway through a glass of orange
juice

00:38.040 --> 00:39.720
I had the strange sense
of foreboding

00:39.720 --> 00:42.760
that in a short time I was going
to actually die.

00:42.760 --> 00:44.480
Medicine isn't real, God.

00:44.480 --> 00:45.280
Why not?

00:45.280 --> 00:47.080
Why not?

00:47.080 --> 00:49.120
You said it was a textbook case
of leukaemia.

00:49.120 --> 00:53.120
We're treating him little boy here,
not a textbook.

02:42.360 --> 02:45.080
In grade school, I used
to have this recurring nightmare

02:45.080 --> 02:46.920
that somebody cancelled
summer vacation.

02:46.920 --> 02:48.320
I used to have that dream too.

02:48.320 --> 02:50.720
Know the difference between that
nightmare and the one I'm having?

02:50.720 --> 02:51.760
What's that?

02:51.760 --> 02:55.760
It used to go away when I woke up.

02:57.320 --> 03:01.320
Mix these up good, Fiscus, I'm on a
considerable losing streak here.

03:06.920 --> 03:10.200
OK, we all know the rules here.

03:10.200 --> 03:14.200
Everybody in the residency
programme, either present
or otherwise,

03:14.320 --> 03:17.320
has put an autograph on a tongue
depressor

03:17.320 --> 03:20.080
in the hat which I now hold.
A little history on the hat.

03:20.080 --> 03:22.120
Who cares about the hat, Fiscus?

03:22.120 --> 03:24.120
Does everyone feel the same
way about the hat?

03:24.120 --> 03:25.720
ALL: Yes!

03:25.720 --> 03:27.320
OK, the no-frills approach.

03:27.320 --> 03:30.200
The first 15 names work
Thanksgiving.

03:30.200 --> 03:33.720
Nothing up my sleeve.

03:33.720 --> 03:34.880
Victor Ehrlich.

03:34.880 --> 03:37.840
Gah!

03:37.840 --> 03:40.200
(LAUGHS)

03:40.200 --> 03:41.840
You didn't shave this morning.

03:41.840 --> 03:44.760
My electric razor's broken.
I'll shave at the hospital.

03:44.760 --> 03:48.240
I thought I'd drive you in today.
I've got to pick up the turkey.

03:48.240 --> 03:51.200
And then I thought I'd pick up
a veal roast for Sunday.

03:51.200 --> 03:53.000
How does that sound?

03:53.000 --> 03:55.920
To be perfectly honest,
I haven't had much appetite lately.

03:55.920 --> 03:57.280
Are you feeling OK?

03:57.280 --> 04:01.280
It's not the cancer,
if that's what you mean.

04:01.360 --> 04:04.400
Well, Jean and Gloria are driving
up with the kids.

04:04.400 --> 04:06.320
Quite a voyage just for Thanksgiving.

04:06.320 --> 04:08.320
And of course Audrey will be over.

04:08.320 --> 04:11.320
Bill's going to the Patriots game,
so he'll be a little late,

04:11.320 --> 04:15.320
but he says he prefers cold
turkey anyway.

04:15.320 --> 04:17.079
Then there's Tom and Linda...

04:17.079 --> 04:19.040
Oh, the Withers can't
make it for dinner.

04:19.040 --> 04:22.960
But they want to
come in for drinks afterwards.

04:22.960 --> 04:26.400
I have this feeling
this will be my last Thanksgiving.

04:26.400 --> 04:28.760
Oh, come on, Daniel.

04:28.760 --> 04:31.280
About a week ago I woke up thirsty.

04:31.280 --> 04:33.560
I went in to get something to drink.

04:33.560 --> 04:35.560
Then the damnedest thing happened.

04:35.560 --> 04:37.720
About halfway through
a glass of orange juice,

04:37.720 --> 04:41.360
I had the strange sense of
foreboding that in a short time...

04:41.360 --> 04:45.360
I was going to actually die.

04:50.040 --> 04:53.320
Would you rather
we did dinner for ourselves?

04:53.320 --> 04:55.280
I can still call off the troops.

04:55.280 --> 04:56.840
No, let's have them all.

04:56.840 --> 05:00.840
Better to go out with a bang
than a whimper.

05:01.440 --> 05:04.920
Wendy Armstrong.

05:04.920 --> 05:08.760
13 down, two to go.

05:08.760 --> 05:11.560
Wayne Fiscus. Holiday doctor.

05:11.560 --> 05:13.880
The last name is...

05:13.880 --> 05:15.440
..Peter White.

05:15.440 --> 05:16.800
White.  Huh?

05:16.800 --> 05:18.960
You're working tomorrow.

05:18.960 --> 05:20.600
OK, Wayne. Thank you.

05:20.600 --> 05:23.200
Take it easy, you guys.

05:23.200 --> 05:25.960
I liked him
better as a hopeless degenerate.

05:25.960 --> 05:27.360
Morning.

05:27.360 --> 05:30.840
I was going home for the first
time in 13 months.

05:30.840 --> 05:33.440
Face it, Victor. Your life is here
and now with us.

05:33.440 --> 05:35.920
My aunt Sharice was sending me
money towards the plane fare.

05:35.920 --> 05:38.320
You can spend that money on
improving your appearance.

05:38.320 --> 05:41.880
I had to work on Diwali day,
and that's a religious violation!

05:41.880 --> 05:43.440
Easter isn't exactly a pagan rite.

05:43.440 --> 05:45.720
Hey, I got to work
on Martin Luther King's birthday.

05:45.720 --> 05:48.480
We don't have a drawing
on Martin Luther King's birthday.

05:48.480 --> 05:51.160
My point exactly.

05:51.160 --> 05:52.960
Hey!

05:52.960 --> 05:56.160
You know, you people should be
ashamed of yourselves.

05:56.160 --> 05:59.200
If you want off on holidays,
go work at Price Chopper.

05:59.200 --> 06:03.040
This isn't just an ordinary job
you got here, for crying out loud.

06:03.040 --> 06:05.320
It's a vocation.

06:05.320 --> 06:07.160
Wonder if he's working tomorrow.

06:07.160 --> 06:08.800
&lt; Not a chance.

06:08.800 --> 06:11.840
Did you have a question, Ehrlich?

06:11.840 --> 06:13.840
No, actually, I was just...

06:13.840 --> 06:15.640
Show a little guts here, Ehrlich.

06:15.640 --> 06:17.560
Repeat the question
so everybody can hear.

06:17.560 --> 06:20.440
Well, we were just speculating,
you know,

06:20.440 --> 06:22.920
if you had special
plans for the holidays, or...

06:22.920 --> 06:26.760
In other words, am I scheduled to
work tomorrow? Correct?

06:26.760 --> 06:28.400
Well, sort of, yeah.

06:28.400 --> 06:29.880
That's a good question, Ehrlich.

06:29.880 --> 06:32.520
Of course I'm not scheduled
to work tomorrow.

06:32.520 --> 06:36.520
I'm a senior staff member, I'm not
required to work on holidays.

06:37.080 --> 06:40.840
I've proven myself
and earned that right.

06:40.840 --> 06:42.400
But I'll tell you what.

06:42.400 --> 06:45.280
I'm just so disgusted with all this
whining,

06:45.280 --> 06:48.040
that I'm going to put myself
on the schedule,

06:48.040 --> 06:52.040
just to show you how a real doctor
should act.

06:52.240 --> 06:56.240
HE WHISTLES "UH-OH"

06:57.400 --> 06:59.640
Good question, Victor(!)

06:59.640 --> 07:01.960
Not only are we spending
the holiday in the hospital,

07:01.960 --> 07:05.960
but now we are spending it with him.

07:14.680 --> 07:16.480
Hi.

07:16.480 --> 07:17.720
What are you reading?

07:17.720 --> 07:21.600
Ten Days That Shook The World.
Seemed appropriate.

07:21.600 --> 07:25.600
I must've graded 10,000 book reports
on it in the past five years,

07:26.400 --> 07:30.360
but I hadn't read the unmolested
version and almost as long.

07:30.360 --> 07:31.920
How does it hold up?

07:31.920 --> 07:33.560
The book is wonderful,

07:33.560 --> 07:37.560
but the reports were
farther off than I thought.

07:38.880 --> 07:40.840
How are my grades?

07:40.840 --> 07:43.480
Oh, boy, you're on the honour roll.

07:43.480 --> 07:46.920
No signs of infection,
improved cardiac function,

07:46.920 --> 07:50.000
blood pressure 120/70.

07:50.000 --> 07:52.120
That's lower than it
was before the transplant.

07:52.120 --> 07:56.120
Well, the blood pressure is
lowered by the medication.

07:56.320 --> 07:57.360
Let me see here.

07:57.360 --> 07:59.240
SHE BREATHES DEEPLY

07:59.240 --> 08:02.800
Overall, your condition is very
promising.

08:02.800 --> 08:05.040
You're making me look good.

08:05.040 --> 08:09.040
Lungs are clear.

08:12.720 --> 08:15.600
Pulse is strong in both arms.

08:15.600 --> 08:17.000
Squeeze my hand.

08:17.000 --> 08:19.720
Ooh! Very good.

08:19.720 --> 08:23.720
So how long do you think it'll be
before I can go back to school?

08:25.480 --> 08:29.480
If you were teaching at Andover or
Deerfield, I'd say about six months,

08:29.680 --> 08:32.159
but in a viper pit
like Paul Revere...

08:32.159 --> 08:33.720
Everybody's been great,

08:33.720 --> 08:37.720
but I thought I was going to be here
for a week. It's s been a month now.

08:38.400 --> 08:39.440
No, huh?

08:39.440 --> 08:40.919
Mmm-mm.

08:40.919 --> 08:43.320
Thanksgiving cards
from some of my kids.

08:43.320 --> 08:45.320
What happened to penmanship,
for Pete's sake?

08:45.320 --> 08:48.920
Hey, if it were perfect,
I wouldn't have to go back.

08:48.920 --> 08:52.920
Yes, well, you're not going anywhere
for a while.

08:53.040 --> 08:57.040
I want you to get some rest. I'll
check back with you tomorrow, OK?

08:57.560 --> 09:01.560
(Bye.)

09:01.800 --> 09:03.000
Morning, Daniel.

09:03.000 --> 09:04.680
Morning.

09:04.680 --> 09:06.800
You read this morning
about the Patriots?

09:06.800 --> 09:08.960
I refuse to read about them.

09:08.960 --> 09:12.320
Never have I seen a team
show such invention in losing.

09:12.320 --> 09:16.320
Come on. Maybe you've given up
on them a little early, huh?

09:20.840 --> 09:23.480
Any coffee in here?

09:23.480 --> 09:27.480
I'll make you some.  Thank you.

09:31.200 --> 09:33.160
Going away for the holidays?

09:33.160 --> 09:34.600
I wish. How about you?

09:34.600 --> 09:38.400
Nope, no plans. Kids are with their
grandparents.

09:38.400 --> 09:39.840
I think I'll stay in bed and read.

09:39.840 --> 09:41.040
I don't blame you.

09:41.040 --> 09:45.040
Sometimes holidays are more work
than work.

09:46.680 --> 09:50.440
Good book?

09:50.440 --> 09:52.480
Not everybody's idea
of a pleasure read.

09:52.480 --> 09:56.480
It looks like it's just
about the right length.

09:58.200 --> 10:00.840
I didn't think you'd like it.

10:00.840 --> 10:03.600
Death With Dignity?

10:03.600 --> 10:06.360
It's an English movement,
hasn't crossed the Atlantic yet.

10:06.360 --> 10:08.160
Thank God.

10:08.160 --> 10:10.480
I don't think he has
much to do with it.

10:10.480 --> 10:13.280
&lt; The English are so much more
civilised about these matters.

10:13.280 --> 10:16.480
Yeah.

10:16.480 --> 10:19.480
I suppose it's personal.

10:19.480 --> 10:22.640
Nothing's more personal.

10:22.640 --> 10:26.280
Have you talked to
Katherine about this?

10:26.280 --> 10:30.000
Suicide is not a polite word
in Katherine's religion.

10:30.000 --> 10:32.440
And not in yours, so I gather.

10:32.440 --> 10:35.720
Daniel, it's none of my business
how a man chooses to go out,

10:35.720 --> 10:39.720
but I know you well enough to
think that this can't be your way.

10:41.560 --> 10:45.560
Oh damn, you're out of luck.
Coffee maker's broken.

10:46.240 --> 10:48.600
Funny thing.

10:48.600 --> 10:50.520
This morning it was
my electric razor.

10:50.520 --> 10:53.320
I suppose if one thing goes,
everything seems to unravel.

10:53.320 --> 10:54.280
KNOCK ON DOOR

10:54.280 --> 10:56.760
KNOCK ON DOOR

10:56.760 --> 10:58.240
Oh, excuse me. I'll come back later.

10:58.240 --> 11:00.320
Oh, excuse me. I'll come back later.

11:00.320 --> 11:03.120
I just wanted to know if you had a
chance to look at the Dempsey case.

11:03.120 --> 11:05.400
Dempsey?

11:05.400 --> 11:06.960
Yeah, it came in last night.

11:06.960 --> 11:10.600
Jaundiced, disoriented, unable
to keep anything down for days.

11:10.600 --> 11:13.280
Looks like we're
heading for liver failure.

11:13.280 --> 11:16.000
Any family history of blood disorders
or enzyme deficiencies?

11:16.000 --> 11:16.760
No.

11:16.760 --> 11:17.800
No.

11:17.800 --> 11:20.240
Yeah, about ten pounds
over the last month.

11:20.240 --> 11:24.240
I left a copy of the history and
a physical on your desk last night.

11:25.720 --> 11:29.720
I ordered all the standard lab
studies plus a lymph node biopsy.

11:32.200 --> 11:35.520
Hmm. I suppose this is what
we euphemistically refer to

11:35.520 --> 11:37.920
as a textbook case.

11:37.920 --> 11:41.920
Nothing like a little
leukaemia to make a holiday.

11:45.640 --> 11:49.040
I'll look in on him
when I have a chance.

11:49.040 --> 11:51.920
Well, I think I'll go down to
the cafeteria for some coffee.

11:51.920 --> 11:52.960
Any takers?

11:52.960 --> 11:56.920
Any takers?

11:56.920 --> 11:58.240
Mind if I borrow this?

11:58.240 --> 12:02.240
Not at all. Don't worry, Donald.
I won't be needing it today.

12:13.320 --> 12:16.840
'Mr Vernon, Mr Ron Vernon
to report to the nurses' station.'

12:16.840 --> 12:18.200
The man of the hour himself.

12:18.200 --> 12:19.440
Pardon?

12:19.440 --> 12:21.600
Mark, I'd be a little remiss
if I didn't tell you

12:21.600 --> 12:23.320
that the whole hospital's buzzing.

12:23.320 --> 12:26.800
Giving up your Thanksgiving to work.
That's inspirational.

12:26.800 --> 12:29.320
Somebody has to set
an example around here.

12:29.320 --> 12:32.760
I'm certainly not above
a little personal sacrifice.

12:32.760 --> 12:34.440
Well, that's big of you, Mark.

12:34.440 --> 12:37.480
Guess that means you're going to
miss the dinner with the in-laws

12:37.480 --> 12:38.800
up in Peterborough this year.

12:38.800 --> 12:41.040
Well, that's the
price I have to pay.

12:41.040 --> 12:43.120
Yeah, I guess Ellen's
going to be disappointed.

12:43.120 --> 12:46.240
No, she'll enjoy herself. She and
her mother get along pretty well.

12:46.240 --> 12:50.200
Do they?
Still, it's a shame, you know.

12:50.200 --> 12:53.120
Look, what I can do,
I can arrange to have you covered

12:53.120 --> 12:56.520
about three o'clock and that'd give
you enough time to drive up there.

12:56.520 --> 12:58.920
Come on, Donald. You know
I can't stand Ellen's family.

12:58.920 --> 13:00.600
They're cretins, for Pete's sake!

13:00.600 --> 13:03.120
This time of year, the drive
to Peterborough's beautiful.

13:03.120 --> 13:07.120
Like taking a sleigh ride
to get root canal work!

13:25.520 --> 13:26.600
Yes, Mrs Jesmer?

13:26.600 --> 13:28.000
Call me Joanne.

13:28.000 --> 13:31.040
Mrs Jesmer, I don't have time to
chat right now. What's the problem?

13:31.040 --> 13:35.040
Well, I'm writing
my girlfriend in Sarasota

13:35.280 --> 13:38.360
and I need to know the
technical name for my disease.

13:38.360 --> 13:41.760
For the last time, you don't have
a disease. You have bunions!

13:41.760 --> 13:45.760
Oh. But isn't there
a more technical name for it?

13:46.120 --> 13:48.880
I mean, something
a little more tragic?

13:48.880 --> 13:51.760
A little bit more tragic.
How about hammer toes?

13:51.760 --> 13:52.920
Really?

13:52.920 --> 13:56.920
Trust me.

14:01.120 --> 14:05.120
Mr Dempsey, I presume.

14:06.680 --> 14:10.680
Joe?

14:11.720 --> 14:14.520
I'm Doctor Auschlander.

14:14.520 --> 14:17.760
Rumour has it you're
not feeling so hot.

14:17.760 --> 14:19.760
You know what, I'm surprised.

14:19.760 --> 14:22.880
Bad enough being sick, but
getting dragged into the hospital

14:22.880 --> 14:25.480
for Thanksgiving can't be
your idea of a great holiday.

14:25.480 --> 14:28.320
Stomach on the blink, right?

14:28.320 --> 14:32.320
Let's have a look.

14:32.680 --> 14:36.680
There we are, now.
That's not going to hurt.

14:36.960 --> 14:40.840
Tender, huh?

14:40.840 --> 14:43.080
Ahh...

14:43.080 --> 14:46.960
Fine. You did that well.

14:46.960 --> 14:49.400
How long's it been
since you kept down your food?

14:49.400 --> 14:51.520
How long's it been
since you kept down your food?

14:51.520 --> 14:53.760
How you been sleeping?

14:53.760 --> 14:55.760
I have a lot of nightmares.

14:55.760 --> 14:59.520
Doctor Morrison says
it's from my temperature.

14:59.520 --> 15:02.360
You're probably feeling
shaken up right now,

15:02.360 --> 15:05.280
and that can give you bad dreams.

15:05.280 --> 15:08.040
I know, cos that's the way
I feel when I go to the doctors.

15:08.040 --> 15:09.360
You do?

15:09.360 --> 15:10.560
You do?

15:10.560 --> 15:12.160
It's perfectly natural to be scared,

15:12.160 --> 15:15.120
even though there's
nothing to be scared of.

15:15.120 --> 15:18.120
You mean I'm not going to die?

15:18.120 --> 15:21.000
Whatever made you think
of a thing like that?

15:21.000 --> 15:22.600
&lt; Everything.

15:22.600 --> 15:24.360
&lt; People treat me funny.

15:24.360 --> 15:26.200
Everyone's always whispering.

15:26.200 --> 15:28.600
Anything else?

15:28.600 --> 15:31.160
&lt; The way my parents look.

15:31.160 --> 15:33.040
&lt; My mother's eyes are always red.

15:33.040 --> 15:36.440
All the tests and stuff.

15:36.440 --> 15:40.440
I don't know. I just know
it's really serious.

15:40.600 --> 15:43.040
&lt; Especially, everybody
says I'm just fine.

15:43.040 --> 15:45.280
And you don't believe them.

15:45.280 --> 15:47.640
I sure don't feel fine.

15:47.640 --> 15:50.400
Well, there's clearly
something wrong, Joe.

15:50.400 --> 15:52.200
But in order to make you better,

15:52.200 --> 15:54.400
we have to find out
what the trouble is,

15:54.400 --> 15:56.200
and that's what the tests are for.

15:56.200 --> 15:58.440
And as for people
treating you differently,

15:58.440 --> 16:01.560
it's because they don't like
to see a boy your age in hospital,

16:01.560 --> 16:03.360
especially your parents.

16:03.360 --> 16:05.400
Are you going to have to operate?

16:05.400 --> 16:07.120
We're just going to
steal a few cells

16:07.120 --> 16:08.640
to find out what the trouble is.

16:08.640 --> 16:12.640
You won't even feel it.
You'll be asleep.

16:15.160 --> 16:19.160
And the kid says, "But Dad,
Mom's busy weighing the milkman." &gt;

16:19.600 --> 16:21.320
I still don't get it.

16:21.320 --> 16:22.680
Ehrlich, it's 11:30.

16:22.680 --> 16:26.240
I want the cardiac scan report
on Eve Leighton on my desk by 12.

16:26.240 --> 16:26.680
But sir...

16:26.680 --> 16:27.720
But sir...

16:27.720 --> 16:29.960
Yes, Doctor Craig.

16:29.960 --> 16:31.400
Hi, guys.

16:31.400 --> 16:32.960
I can't eat this hamster meat!

16:32.960 --> 16:35.000
I love Salisbury steak.

16:35.000 --> 16:36.080
&lt; Peter's found a new drug.

16:36.080 --> 16:38.840
&lt; Peter's found a new drug.

16:38.840 --> 16:40.240
Among other things.  Like what?

16:40.240 --> 16:41.440
Eating here tomorrow.

16:41.440 --> 16:43.240
Eating here tomorrow.

16:43.240 --> 16:45.560
If we can't be out of the
hospital for Thanksgiving,

16:45.560 --> 16:47.960
we'll just bring Thanksgiving
here to the hospital.

16:47.960 --> 16:49.320
Have our own dinner right here.

16:49.320 --> 16:52.920
Everybody make their own
speciality. It'll be fun. &gt;

16:52.920 --> 16:54.840
Your drug is very strong.

16:54.840 --> 16:58.840
What do you think, huh?

17:01.880 --> 17:04.680
Tomorrow's menu.

17:04.680 --> 17:07.440
OK, Wendy, what's your speciality?

17:07.440 --> 17:10.079
Erm...teriyaki and green beans.

17:10.079 --> 17:12.040
My mother makes them
every Thanksgiving.

17:12.040 --> 17:13.079
My mother makes them
every Thanksgiving.

17:13.079 --> 17:16.400
&lt; Mutter paneer.

17:16.400 --> 17:17.560
Spell it.

17:17.560 --> 17:20.720
Just put cheese balls and yoghurt.

17:20.720 --> 17:22.800
